AB  - As the 77 million baby boomers who brought people the sexual revolution inexorably age, they will face a striking paradox. The ignorance, prejudice, and silence about sex and sexuality they fought so hard to upend are still alive and well in old age. In May 2011, in a colloquium sponsored by The Harry & Jeanette Weinberg Center for Elder Abuse Prevention, the Roosevelt House Public Policy Institute at Hunter College served as an historic backdrop for a daylong discussion about sex and aging, examining the subject across a spectrum -- as a health, human rights, social service, criminal justice, victim assistance, and ethical issue. In the largest ever study on sex and aging, researchers interviewed 3,005 community-dwelling people, ages 57 to 85, about their sexual practices, assessed their health status, and examined the correlation between the two. Overall, the study found that while sexuality declines with age, most older adults remain sexually active and report that sex remains an important part of life. Adapted from the source document.
